</taxonomicName>
species groups
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,1086,1291]" pageId="6" pageNumber="201">
The male genitalia of 
<taxonomicName box="[402,521,1086,1110]" class="Insecta" family="Elmidae" genus="Macrelmis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="201" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[402,521,1086,1110]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="201">Macrelmis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been underestimated in its taxonomic use. 
<bibRefCitation author="Hinton" box="[1060,1221,1086,1111]" pageId="6" pageNumber="201" refString="Hinton, H. E. (1940) A monographic revision of the Mexican water beetles of the family Elmidae. Novitates Zoologicae, 42 (2), 217 - 396." type="journal article" year="1940">
Hinton (
<number box="[1154,1212,1087,1111]" pageId="6" pageNumber="201" value="1940.0">1940</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
already stated that the male genitalia has important characters to identify and classify species. The use of paramere and aedeagus characters tends to lead to less equivocal identification due to its stable morphology. So, we propose a new definition for the species group based mainly on male genitalia, but also including pronotal, elytral and leg characters, when possible (see 
<tableCitation box="[523,612,1230,1255]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="7.[151,239,368,391]" captionText="TABLE 1. Diagnostic characters of the species groups." pageId="6" pageNumber="201">
Table 
<number box="[599,612,1231,1255]" pageId="6" pageNumber="201" value="1.0">1</number>
</tableCitation>
). This way, the groups established by Hinton and other authors are reformulated and new groups are proposed. They are presented in alphabetical order.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
